{
  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game centers on trading privately valued red and blue chips plus common-value green chips. Each player starts with 10 of each color. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone, so trades involving green are essentially transfers of certain, shared value. Red and blue values differ by player: buffalo (Bf) strongly prefers blue ($0.70) and dislikes red ($0.10); bear (Br) values both red ($0.60) and blue ($1.00) highly; goose (G) is nearly indifferent between red and blue at very low values ($0.10 each). This creates large potential gains from trade between Bf and Br in blue-for-red, and moderate gains when swapping high-value chips (to someone) for green with G, who may be more indifferent. However, players only know their own chip values, so initial rounds feature exploratory offers that test which directions of trade get acceptance. Simultaneous private responses and random tie-breaking over multiple acceptors create strategic uncertainty: proposers cannot perfectly target a partner and may worry about losing surplus to another acceptor. Personas suggest all three are empathetic and not strongly punitive. Buffalo is reflective, inequality-tolerant, and likely to think numerically, so she will craft surplus-positive trades but may tolerate others capturing more surplus if it secures her gains. Bear is patient and somewhat intuitive, valuing both red and blue and likely to experiment with green-for-red or green-for-blue to see who bites, with some concern about exploitation. Goose is logical, patient, and inequality-tolerant with weak norm enforcement; she may accept small but strictly positive gains and remain relatively unconcerned about others’ payoffs. Across three short rounds, we should see a transition from small, information-seeking probes to at least one substantial, clearly surplus-creating trade once individual patterns of acceptance become somewhat inferred from earlier moves, especially involving bear’s high blue valuation and buffalo’s dislike of red.",
