    {
      "round": 1,
      "round_explanation": "By Round 1, players have learned that buffalo and bear can create strong bilateral surplus from exchanging red and blue, while green-for-red offers at roughly break-even terms for bear were declined—suggesting others either dislike giving up green value or do not see red as sufficiently attractive. Goose’s declined offer to buy green with red also indicates that neither buffalo nor bear are eager to trade away their safe green for low-value red, reinforcing perceived low market value of red to at least one counterpart. In this context, buffalo is likely to double down on red-for-blue trades, possibly shading terms slightly more in her favor now that she has seen bear’s willingness to accept. Bear may update that buffalo especially dislikes red and strongly values blue, and that goose is cautious about giving up green; she may attempt a more generous or differently structured offer, such as moving some blue or red for green in a way that entices either partner. Goose, having seen only one successful trade (benefiting both buffalo and bear), may attempt a more modest, clearly positive-sum proposal that shifts a few low-value red or blue chips into green without asking for large green quantities.",
