    {
      "round": 2,
      "round_explanation": "Going into the final round, buffalo and bear have repeatedly executed mutually beneficial red–blue trades, and bear and goose have completed at least one blue-for-green exchange. These outcomes signal fairly clearly that: (1) bear highly values both red and blue and is willing to swap them for green under favorable ratios; (2) buffalo wants to shed red for blue and is not keen to trade away green; and (3) goose is willing to part with some green if compensated with blue at seemingly generous terms, but not for small amounts of red. With only one round remaining, players will prioritize easy, low-friction deals: buffalo may attempt one last red-for-blue trade with bear, bear may try to fine-tune a green-for-blue or green-for-red swap that someone will accept, and goose may either take a final small gain if an attractive offer appears or make one more cautious proposal. Risk of rejection still exists due to incomplete information and each player’s concern about not ending worse off, but prior history narrows the likely directions of trade and terms that appear acceptable.",
