  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features common-value green chips and privately valued red/blue chips. All players start with 10 of each color.\n\nPrivate values:\n- badger-red-5032 (Badger): RED=$0.80, BLUE=$0.80, GREEN=$0.50\n- camel-yellow-5577 (Camel): RED=$0.60, BLUE=$0.40, GREEN=$0.50\n- squid-yellow-9545 (Squid): RED=$0.20, BLUE=$0.60, GREEN=$0.50\n\nKey incentive patterns:\n- Badger: Symmetric high value for RED and BLUE (both $0.80), higher than GREEN ($0.50). Badger is happy to swap GREEN for either RED or BLUE at better than 5:8 (≈0.625) price, and will be reluctant to give up RED/BLUE except at a premium.\n- Camel: Values RED ($0.60) > GREEN ($0.50) > BLUE ($0.40). Camel wants to convert BLUE into RED or GREEN and will be less eager to give up RED unless getting strong compensation.\n- Squid: Values BLUE ($0.60) > GREEN ($0.50) >> RED ($0.20). Squid is happy to dump RED into BLUE or GREEN at almost any reasonable rate, but is reluctant to part with BLUE.\n\nSurplus opportunities:\n- RED surplus trades between Badger and Squid: Badger values RED at $0.80, Squid at $0.20, a $0.60 wedge. Squid should want to send away RED for BLUE or GREEN; Badger wants to acquire RED from Squid.\n- BLUE surplus trades between Badger and Camel: Badger values BLUE at $0.80, Camel at $0.40, a $0.40 wedge. Camel should want to trade away BLUE in exchange for RED or GREEN; Badger wants BLUE from Camel.\n- BLUE between Camel and Squid: Squid $0.60 vs Camel $0.40, a $0.20 wedge; however, both like BLUE more than GREEN, so direct Camel–Squid BLUE–GREEN trades are less attractive than involving Badger.\n\nUncertainty and reasoning:\n- Each player sees others’ proposals and acceptances but not their valuations. Over 3 rounds, they can infer relative preferences (e.g., who is eager to buy RED or BLUE) but not exact numbers.\n- Because all are strong logical reasoners with moderate-to-high cooperation orientation, they are likely to seek positive-sum trades that give everyone a non-negative surplus while avoiding obvious exploitation, especially early.\n- However, the rule that multiple acceptances are resolved by random selection creates coordination risk: proposers cannot target a specific partner. They must design offers that (a) are good enough that at least one partner will accept, but (b) in early moves, may not be too attractive to both if they want to learn who values what.\n\nLikely dynamics:\n- Early in Round 0, Badger will test the market with a safe, slightly favorable trade that reveals interest in converting lower-valued chips (GREEN) into higher-valued chips (RED/BLUE) without overpaying.\n- Camel, trusting and tolerant of inequality, will likely propose trades that slightly favor others but move BLUE into better-valued colors.\n- Squid, empathic and a strong reasoner, will search for trades that reduce low-valued RED holdings and increase BLUE while not making blatant sacrifices.\n\nOver the three rounds, we should expect:\n- At least one mutually beneficial accepted trade that moves RED from Squid or Camel to Badger, or BLUE from Camel/Squid to Badger.\n- Some exploratory or overly favorable proposals that are declined when they impose a loss on one potential recipient.\n- Gradual convergence toward each player holding more of their personally high-valued chips and fewer low-valued ones, within the constraint of only 9 proposer turns.",
