  "game_explanation": "This 3-player bargaining game centers on trading red and blue chips, which have different private values to each player, while green chips are common-value and thus strategically neutral except as a way to smooth trades. Each player starts with 10 of each color and acts three times as proposer, once per round, in a fixed order. Because each player privately values chips differently, there are clear surplus-creating opportunities: for example, both whale-red-86 and duck-orange-4971 value RED at $1.00, while dolphin-orange-3122 values RED at $0.60; conversely, dolphin values BLUE at $0.80, higher than whale at $0.40 and duck at $0.60. That means efficient gains come from transferring RED from dolphin to whale or duck, and BLUE from whale to dolphin. GREEN is worth $0.50 to everyone and gives no surplus by itself, but can be used like cash or a tie-breaker in multi-round bargaining.\n\nThe players’ personas suggest generally cooperative, inequality-tolerant behavior with moderate caution against exploitation. None has particularly strong norm-enforcement, so they are unlikely to reject small, positive but unequal gains just to punish others. They also see a calculator that tells them exactly their own gain or loss for each proposal, so they should never accept strictly negative expected-value trades. However, because they do not know others’ values, they must infer them from observed proposals and acceptances. Early in the game, they will test the waters with modest, positive-surplus offers and adjust based on who accepts. Over only three rounds, there is limited time for complex reputation strategies, so they will focus on obviously beneficial trades rather than multi-step setups.\n\nIn this forecast, whale-red-86, as a highly cooperative and relatively numerate player who values RED the most and BLUE the least, will often attempt to trade BLUE away to dolphin-orange-3122 in exchange for RED, since that is the clearest surplus opportunity. Dolphin, who values BLUE highly and RED relatively little, is a natural counterpart and will tend to accept any trade that increases his dollar value even if it appears somewhat unequal. Duck-orange-4971, with high RED and moderate BLUE values and very low norm-enforcement, is willing to accept modest gains, and is also a good target for selling BLUE or GREEN in exchange for RED.\n\nA key uncertainty is competition for favorable offers: when a proposer makes a profitable trade for more than one counterpart, multiple players may accept, forcing a random draw that the proposer cannot control. This risk will make proposers slightly conservative in sizing offers: they may try to gain value even if only one of the possible counterparts has strong incentives, but keep trades simple enough that exploiting common-value GREEN doesn’t cause unnecessary competition. Across three rounds, we expect: (1) early feeling-out proposals where others may decline if surplus is too small; (2) mid-game convergence on clearer cross-valuation opportunities (RED from dolphin to whale/duck, BLUE from whale to dolphin/duck); and (3) late-game attempts by each player to grab a final, possibly slightly aggressive gain given that there is no continuation payoff beyond round 2.\n\nThe reconstructed play below respects the private incentives given the valuations and personas: all accepted trades are strictly profitable to both sides given their own values, declined trades are unprofitable or too small to be attractive under mild caution, and the pattern of who trades with whom is consistent with the obvious comparative advantage in RED and BLUE values.",
