itive gains (a few cents) can be acceptable given low norm-enforcement and mild cooperation orientations, but offers that are close to zero or slightly negative for responders will usually be declined. Across just three rounds, each with one turn per player, players have limited time to learn others’ values, so initial offers will be exploratory, roughly fair-looking, and simple (small integer ratios like 1-for-1 or 2-for-1), gradually moving toward more exploitative or more tailored trades if they see clear acceptance patterns. Because all three have the same GREEN value, GREEN chips are most likely used as a flexible medium to balance RED/BLUE reallocation: it is natural to see proposals that pay GREEN to acquire the more valuable private-color chips (RED for peacock, BLUE for swan, either for bear). With only nine total proposals and no communication, the likely path is: round 0 features cautious, almost ‘fair’ trials with small surplus; round 1 starts to exploit revealed preferences (e.g., others’ willingness to give up specific colors); round 2 focuses on final value-improving trades, mainly RED to peacock and BLUE to swan, mediated by GREEN or directly against the opposite color. Declines are most likely when proposals impose any loss on a responder or when a responder expects that better terms may come later, while accepted trades will typically generate clear, easy-to-see gains on the surplus calculator.",
