sk multi-acceptance; then a random recipient is chosen. Players therefore avoid offering deals that are strongly attractive to both non-senders unless they are roughly indifferent to which recipient they get. Most trades will be simple one-color-for-one-color or small integer ratio swaps that visibly increase the proposer’s value without obviously harming the recipient.\n\nGiven only three rounds and three turns per round, dynamics are short-horizon: players cannot rely on long-run reputation. They will typically start modestly in Round 0—testing others’ willingness to buy/sell specific colors—then refine offers in Rounds 1–2 using observed acceptances/declines to infer who likes which colors. Because all three are prosocial and not strict norm enforcers, we expect a few mutually beneficial trades to execute, focused around reallocating BLUE from dog to owl and some RED/BLUE between mouse and owl. Some apparently favorable proposals might still be declined if they look too skewed or confusing given limited information about others’ valuations.\n\nOverall, the likely trajectory: early tentative trade attempts (some declined), then a couple of clearly positive-sum swaps as preferences become clearer, with owl gradually increasing BLUE holdings, dog offloading some BLUE for RED/GREEN, and mouse making at least one mild surplus-improving trade while avoiding big downside risk.",
