r loss from every possible deal, so all accept/decline decisions are individually rational in terms of their own payoffs. The main uncertainties are about others’ valuations and future proposal opportunities: players know they only have three rounds of three proposals, and they must balance waiting for better deals against the risk that no one will offer them a clearly beneficial trade later. Early in the game, proposals are likely to be relatively simple, exploratory exchanges using green as a safe counterpart; as history unfolds, players can infer that lion is likely offloading red/blue, while iguana and alligator are willing buyers for blue and, to a lesser extent, red. Because multiple acceptances lead to a random partner, proposers must craft deals that are attractive to at least one target without being too generous to the other possible respondent. That randomness encourages symmetric-looking offers that can plausibly be accepted by either high-blue player. Over three rounds, we expect a few accepted trades that transfer blue (and some red) away from lion toward iguana and alligator, with iguana slightly more willing than alligator to take on riskier or thinner-margin deals, while alligator’s higher exploitation caution makes her selective and sometimes leaves mutually beneficial but uncertain trades on the table.",
