  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features common-value green chips and privately valued red and blue chips. Everyone starts with 10 of each color, but their dollar values differ by person: alligator values red highest (0.60) relative to blue (0.50) and green (0.50); buffalo is fairly balanced with mild preference for red (0.50) over blue (0.20) but equal to green (0.50); rabbit strongly prefers red (1.00) over green (0.50) and blue (0.30). This structure creates clear gains from trade: in particular, rabbit and alligator both value red more than buffalo does, while buffalo cares relatively more about turning low-value blue into green/red. Green is common-value at 0.50 for everyone, so trading red or blue for green makes sense when it allows a player to move chips away from their lowest-valued color. However, each player only observes their own values; they see the public range for reds and blues (0.10–1.00), so they know others may value some colors very differently.\n\nGiven their personas, alligator is a logical, inequality-tolerant reasoner focused on maximizing own payoff and not strongly enforcing fairness, so we expect calculated but somewhat self-focused proposals that secure at least small positive surplus. Buffalo is cooperation-oriented and generosity-forward, often willing to accept mutually beneficial or even slightly disadvantageous trades to keep things moving and avoid uncertainty. Rabbit is prosocial and reflective, but also inequality-tolerant and less guarded, so she tends to accept favorable or mildly unbalanced offers if they help others and still leave her better off. Because responders see their exact net gain/loss in real time, blatantly negative-sum offers for them are almost always rejected; the bargaining happens over positive-sum, roughly fair-seeming splits where one side might gain a bit more.\n\nThe main strategic tension comes from asymmetric information about valuations and the random resolution when multiple players accept. Proposers cannot target a specific responder; if both non-senders would gain and accept, the realized partner is chosen randomly. That encourages proposers to frame trades that are reasonably attractive to both potential partners, or where they are indifferent between which partner they actually trade with. Over the three rounds, each player has three proposal opportunities. Because no leftover chips carry to other games and there is no explicit penalty for failed trades, people often become more flexible over time, especially the more cooperative players.\n\nWe therefore anticipate that early moves will involve cautious, simple, one-color-for-one-color swaps that offer both sides a small positive surplus. As players observe who accepts what, they adjust expectations of others’ likely valuations. Alligator’s reasoning ability and low norm-enforcement drive him toward clean arbitrage-like trades that exploit likely undervaluation of some colors by others. Buffalo’s cooperation orientation makes her a frequent accepter of modest-gain trades, especially when she can convert low-value blue into higher-value red or green. Rabbit’s strong red preference means she is willing to give up some green and blue to build up red holdings, accepting deals that look slightly tilted but clearly beneficial. The forecast below describes one plausible full playthrough, with modest but consistent gains for all three as they gradually discover and exploit value differences.",
  "rounds": [
